narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: A fundamental understanding of calculus in three dimensions and more, and a spatial perspective on geometrical and integral concepts.

Techniques to solve complex derivatives, double integral and triple integral. A deeper and clear understanding of space function and its gradient. Knowledge of vector field and corresponding curl, divergence which would be useful in later physical classes.
Essential skills of multivariable calculus and vector calculus.
double integrals, vector integrals, line integrals, volume, etc.
Academic material typically found in a Calculus III course.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The workshops could be worth less of the overall grade.

Strength: many useful in-class discussion and workshop practices. The workload is just perfect and lecture notes are easy to follow and clear enough even under online teaching mode.

weakness: the first two exams do not match the lesson schedule exactly. For example, the last class we take before the exam1 would not appear in exam2 but actually in exam2, this may cause confusion when reviewing the lecture notes. I think it is better to schedule the exam right after the period of first part and then second part.

Very fast-paced, I think faster feedback through grades and extra communication would improve the course.
well-organized with video lectures and lecture notes.
A ton of material and not enough time to practice it.

Strengths: Workshops, PSETS, and tests were all sufficiently challenging and fair. Online resources such as Ximera were very useful. Good textbook.

Weaknesses: Recorded lectures were sometimes confusing. Class time spent going over lectures felt like an inefficient use of time. Latter half of course seems only relevant to physics majors.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes. Good instructor, well structured, good workload.
I would recommend this course to anybody considering getting to the next level in mathematics.
I would recommend you take this class during a full semester (fall or spring), not during the summer, unless you are taking only this class and are able to commit a lot of time to it.
Not over the summer at all. It was too much material for too few days. It wasnt necessarily hard but it was very hard to practice it to learn it and keep it in your head.
Only if you need to take it to advance further in your major.
